  2. After we roll the die \(n\) times, we denote the numbers we actually observe as \(x_1,...,x_n\). For example, if we see a \(4\) on the \(i\)-th roll, we would write \(x_i=4\) (not \(X_i = 4\)).

  3. Any expression involving \(X_1,...,X_n\) corresponds to the time before we have observed the data. Each \(X_i\) is a RV.

  4. Any expression involving \(x_1,...,x_n\) corresponds to the time after we have observed the data. The \(x_i\) values are just the outcomes of the experiment (they are not RVs).

9.3 Numerical Summaries

Suppose we have a collection of IID RVs \(X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_n\) with \(E(X_i)= \mu\) and \(\text{var}(X_i)=\sigma^2\) (both unknown). We do an experiment and observe the values of \(x_1,...,x_n\). How do summarise the data?

9.3.1 Sample Mean

Definition 9.1 Given the observations \(x_1,x_2,...,x_n\), we define the sample mean to be \[\bar x = \frac{1}{n}\sum^n_{i=1}x_i.\]

Note that before we collect any data the RV \[\label{Xbar} \bar{X}=\frac{1}{n}\sum^n_{i=1}X_i\] is effectively a ‘formula’ for calculating the sample mean from the IID RVs \(X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_n\). You should not confuse \(\bar x\) or \(\bar X\) with \(\mu\). The difference between these three ‘means’ is very important.

9.3.2 Sample Variance

Definition 9.2 Given the observations \(x_1,x_2,...,x_n\), we define the sample variance to be \[s^2 = \frac{1}{n-1}\sum^n_{i=1}(x_i-\bar x)^2=\frac{1}{n-1}\left(\sum^n_{i=1}x_i^2-n\bar x^2\right).\]

Again before we collect any data the RV \[S^2=\frac{1}{n-1}\sum^n_{i=1}(X_i-\bar X)^2=\frac{1}{n-1}\left(\sum^n_{i=1}X_i^2-n\bar X^2\right)\] is effectively a ‘formula’ for calculating the sample variance. You should not confuse \(s^2\) or \(S^2\) with \(\sigma^2\).

The use of \(n-1\) in the denominator is a little surprising (intuitively \(n\) would make more sense). The use of \(n-1\) results in \(S^2\) being an ‘unbiased estimator’ of \(\sigma^2\).

9.3.3 Sample Correlation

Given the observations \((x_1,y_1)\), \((x_2,y_2)\), ..., \((x_n,y_n)\) we define the sample correlation coefficient (sometimes called Pearson’s correlation coefficient) to be \[r=\frac{\sum(x_i-\bar x)(y_i-\bar y)}{\sqrt{\sum(x_i-\bar x)^2\sum(y_i-\bar y)^2}}=\frac{\sum x_iy_i-n\bar x\bar y}{\sqrt{(\sum x_i^2-n\bar x^2)(\sum y_i^2-n\bar y^2)}}.\] Note that:

  1. \(-1\leq r \leq 1\).

  2. \(r\) measures linear correlation. \(|r|\) is close to \(1\) when the \((x_i,y_i)\) pairs are close to a straight line on a scatter plot. If they are strongly related, but in a non-linear way, \(r\) can be close to \(0\).

Example 9.1 We collected data from eight female students on their height in centimeters, these are given below: \[160\text{, } 165\text{, } 180\text{, } 157\text{, } 172\text{, } 175\text{, } 145\text{, } 152\] calculate the mean and variance of the sample.

Solution:

\[\bar x=163.25cm\] \[s^2=\frac{1}{7}\left(214212-8\times163.25^2\right)=143.93cm^2.\]

9.4 Inference

In statistical inference, we use information from a suitable sample to draw conclusions about a much larger population of interest which cannot be examined in its entirety. In many cases, the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) in Definition 8.2 plays a key role. For example if \(X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_n\) are IID RVs we can see that \(\bar X\) in Equation (8.1) will be normal if \(n\) is large enough (by the CLT). The distribution of \(\bar X\) is called the sampling distribution and tells us how far away from \(\mu\) the sample mean is likely to be. In this case we use \(\bar x\) as the estimate of \(\mu\).

9.5 Estimation

Our objective here is to find a sensible estimate of the parameters of a probability distribution.

9.5.1 Terminology and Notation

An estimator is some function of RVs (typically IID \(X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_n\)) which we use to estimate some parameter. Its actual numerical value is called the estimate.

Example 9.2 Suppose a RV \(X\) representing some interesting feature about a population is believed to follow an Exp\((\lambda)\) distribution. Suppose we sample \(n\) values of \(X\) (\(X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_n\)). Assuming that \(X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_n\) are independent we have \(n\) IID RVs each with an Exp\((\lambda)\) distribution. Recall from Definition 6.7 that \(E(X_i)=1/\lambda\) and Var\((X_i)=1/\lambda^2\). The CLT (Definition 8.2) states that \[\bar X \sim N\left(\frac{1}{\lambda},\frac{1}{n\lambda^2}\right).\] This result implies a potential estimator of \(\lambda\) could be the reciprocal of the sample mean. We write this as \[\begin{align} \hat\lambda &= \frac{1}{\bar X} \\ &= \frac{n}{X_1 + X_2 + \ldots + X_n}. \end{align}\]
and once we have observed \(x_1,x_2,...,x_n\) the actual numerical estimate is \[\hat\lambda=\frac{1}{\bar x}.\] Suppose we sample 100 values from the population and observe a sample mean of 12.6 then our estimate of \(\lambda\) is \(\hat\lambda = 1/12.6 = 0.08\)

Note that we put a ‘hat’ over the parameter being estimated to denote that it is an estimator. So \(\hat \lambda\) is an estimator of \(\lambda\).

9.5.2 Methods of Estimation

The approach in Example 9.2 is sensible but restricted to certain situations. We need a well defined procedure to use in all cases. There are two common estimation methods: least squares and maximum likelihood.

Least squares estimation is useful because it does not make any assumptions about the probabilitydistribution of the RVs, only about their expectations. Maximum likelihood estimationdoes require a probability distribution to be specified, but has the advantage that we can assess how close our estimates are likely to be to their target. For this reason, maximum likelihood is the most commonly used estimation method. We do not either estimation method here but Least Squares estimation is covered next semester.

9.5.3 Unbiased Estimators

A desirable property of an estimator is that it should be unbiased. For an estimator \(\hat\theta\) of a parameter \(\theta\) we define the bias as \[\text{bias}=E\left(\hat\theta\right)-\theta\] If \(E\left(\hat\theta\right)=\theta\) then the bias is 0 and ‘on average’ the estimator gives the correct value. Estimators with zero bias are called unbiased estimators.

Example 9.3 Suppose \(X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_n\) are \(n\) IID RVs each with \(E(X_i)= \mu\). Then \[\hat \mu = \frac{1}{n}\sum^n_{i=1}X_i\] is an unbiased estimator of \(\mu\). To verify this we need to show that \(E(\hat \mu) = \mu\). \[\begin{align} E(\hat \mu) &= E\left( \frac{1}{n}\sum^n_{i=1}X_i\right) \\ &= \frac{1}{n} \sum^n_{i=1}E(X_i) \\ &= \mu \; \text{since} \; E(X_i)=\mu \end{align}\] Hence \(\hat \mu\) is an unbiased estimator of \(\mu\).

9.6 Confidence intervals

A single best guess at a parameter value \(\theta\) is of some use but we also need to give an idea of our uncertainty in the estimate. We usually do this by providing an interval in which \(\theta\) is likely to lie, with some level of certainty.

To specify a confidence interval (CI) we first need to decide on a confidence level which is usually expressed as a percentage and is typically 95%. Confidence levels are often misinterpreted. It is incorrect to say that the interval contains the true parameter value with 95% probability (it either contains it or it doesn’t). Instead you should make statements about the process that generates them. It is correct to say that 95% of intervals constructed in this way are expected to contain the true parameter value.

We now identify the \(\alpha\) level associated with our confidence level. Let \(c\) be the confidence level expressed as a decimal, then \[\alpha ~=~ 1-c\] eg 95% is associated with \(\alpha=0.05\). We use this \(\alpha\) to specify quantiles for calculation of the CIs.

9.6.1 CI for mean of Normal data, \(\sigma^2\) known

Let \(X_1,X_2,...,X_n\) be a random sample from a normal distribution \(N(\mu,\sigma^2)\) with unknown \(\mu\) and known \(\sigma^2\). \(X_1,X_2,...,X_n\) are therefore IID RVs with \(E(X_i) = \mu\).

A \(100(1-\alpha)\)% confidence interval for \(\mu\) is centred at \(\bar X\) and is given by \[\left(\bar X-z_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}},\bar X+z_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right)\] often written as \[\bar X\pm z_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\] where \(z_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\) solves \(\Phi\left(z_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\right)=1-\frac{\alpha}{2}\) and is evaluated using MatLab’s quantile function norminv\((1-\frac{\alpha}{2},0,1)\). Remember that at this stage, before collecting any data, \(\bar X\) is a RV.

Example 9.4 Components are produced from a machine with standard deviation \(0.08\)kg and are supposed to have mean weight \(0.6\)kg. A sample of \(30\) components has an average weight of \(0.63\)kg. Calculate a \(95\%\) confidence level for \(\mu\) and comment on whether the machine should be repaired.

Solution:

We have \(\overline{x} = 0.63, \sigma = 0.08\) and \(n = 30\). For \(95\%\) we use \(\alpha = 0.05\) and \(z_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}} = 1.96\). The confidence interval is therefore \[\begin{align} \overline{x} \pm z_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} &= 0.63 \pm 1.96 \times \frac{0.08}{\sqrt{30}}\\ &= 0.63 \pm 0.0286\\ &= (0.6014,0.6586) \end{align}\] There is therefore good evidence that the machine is faulty as the intended mean \(0.6\) lies outside the confidence interval.

9.6.2 CI for mean of Normal data, \(\sigma^2\) unknown

If we don’t know \(\sigma^2\) we estimate it from the data by \(S^2\), but then we must modify our sampling distribution. It is no longer a normal distribution but is now has a Student \(t\) distribution with \(n-1\) degrees of freedom (where \(n\) is the number of data points used to construct the interval). You don’t need to know why this is true.

The \(t\) distribution is a distribution similar to \(N(0,1)\) symmetric about \(0\), but lower it has fatter tails especially for small \(n\). You can calculate \(t\) quantiles in MatLab with \(tinv(p,\nu)\) where \(p\) is the probability \(\left(1-\frac{\alpha}{2}\right)\) and \(\nu\) is the degrees of freedom.

A \(100(1-\alpha)\)% confidence interval for \(\mu\) is given by \[\overline{X} \pm t_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{S}{\sqrt{n}}\] where \(S\) is the sample standard deviation.

Example 9.5 Suppose we have the scenario of Example 9.4, but regard the standard deviation as unknown. If we estimate it by the sample standard deviation of \(0.078\)kg, calculate an appropriate CI for \(\mu\) and comment on how it differs from the previous CI.

Solution:

We have \(\overline{x} = 0.63, s = 0.078\) and \(n = 30\). For \(95\%\) we use \(\alpha = 0.05\) and \(t_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}} = 2.0452\) using tinv(0.975,29).

The confidence interval is therefore \[\begin{align} \overline{x} \pm t_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}} &= 0.63 \pm 2.0452 \times \frac{0.078}{\sqrt{30}}\\ &= 0.63 \pm 0.0291\\ &= (0.6009,0.6591) \end{align}\] This is slightly wider than before, even with a smaller standard deviation, because we have extra uncertainty in our estimation because \(\sigma^2\) is unknown.

10 Hypothesis Testing

In hypothesis testing we try and assess what evidence the data provide regarding the plausibility of various hypotheses.

Hypotheses can be of many types; we will only cover two of these:

  • A parameter takes a specified value, e.g. \(H_0:\mu=2\).

  • A particular probability model is applicable (the “goodness of fit” problem), e.g. \(H_0\): accident counts follow a Poisson distribution.

10.1 Test procedure

As before we assume that we have a random sample of data which we consider to be IID RVs.

The null hypothesis \(H_0\) reflects what we will continue to believe unless the data suggests otherwise. We then specify an alternative hypothesis (usually the complement of \(H_0\)) and denote it \(H_1\) (or \(H_A\)).

Next we define the test statistic. This is a function of the data that measures how much it ‘disagrees with’ \(H_0\). The test statistic will have a known sampling distribution (called the null sampling distribution) under the assumption that \(H_0\) is true . We then check whether our observed test statistic looks consistent with the null sampling distribution or not. Essentially this means looking to see whether the observed test statistic is near the middle of the null sampling distribution or in the tails.

To decide whether the observed test statistic is consistent with \(H_0\), we have to state how small aprobability is surprising (our significance level). Typically this is (arbitrarily) set at 5% but other values are sometimes used (e.g. 10% or 1%). We then identify the quantiles of the null sampling distribution that correspond to this probability and then check our observed test statistics against these quantiles. We illustrate the procedure with some examples.

10.2 One sample \(z\) tests

Assume that our IID RVs (sampled data) follow a \(N(\mu ,\sigma^2)\) distribution with \(\sigma^2\) known. We are interested in testing a null hypothesis \[H_0: \mu=\mu_0\] we use a one sample \(z\) test. Our test statistic is \[Z=\frac{\bar X - \mu_0}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\] which has a null sampling distribution \(Z \sim N(0,1)\). Recall the \(2\sigma\)-rule reproduced in Figure 10.1.

Figure 10.1: The PDF of a \(N(0,1)\) random variable. The unshaded area is 0.95

If \(Z\sim N(0,1)\), then \(P(-1.96\leq Z\leq1.96)=0.95\), so there is a 5% chance that either \(Z<-1.96\) or \(Z>1.96\). If the test statistic has an absolute value greater than 1.96 then it is in the tails of the null sampling distribution (at the 5% level) and we would reject \(H_0\) at this level. Take care when calculating your quantiles; for a combined 5% probability in both tails, you look up the value giving \(2.5\)% in each tail for example norminv\((0.975,0,1)\). It is common to approximate 1.96 by 2.

Example 10.1 The volume of liquid in cartons produced by a particular machine is modelled as a \(N(\mu, 6^2)\) distribution. A sample of \(30\) cartons from this machine gives an average volume of \(566\) ml. Test the hypothesis that the mean amount of fluid is \(568\) ml at the \(10\%\) level.

Solution:

Our null and alternative hypotheses

  • \(H_0: \mu = 568\),

  • \(H_1: \mu \neq 568\).

We can now calculate our test statistic to be \[z =\displaystyle \frac{\overline{x} - \mu_0}{\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}} = \frac{566 - 568}{\frac{6}{\sqrt{30}}} = -1.83.\] We compare the absolute value of the test statistic to the 0.95 quantile of the standard normal distribution. \(z_{0.95} = 1.645\) and since \(|-1.83| > 1.645\) we have sufficient evidence to reject \(H_0\) at the 10% level.

10.3 One sample \(t\) tests

As in Section 9.6.2, if we do not know \(\sigma^2\) and have to estimate it from the data by the sample variance \(S^2\). Our test statistic is \[T=\frac{\bar X - \mu_0}{s/\sqrt{n}}\] The sampling distribution of T under the null hypothesis is now the \(t_{n-1}\) distribution so we use \(t\) rather than \(z\) quantiles. The procedure is otherwise the same. This is called the one-sample \(t\) test.

Example 10.2 The volume of liquid in cartons produced by a particular machine is modelled as a \(N(\mu, \sigma^2)\) distribution where \(\sigma^2\) is unknown. A sample of \(30\) cartons from this machine gives an average volume of \(566\) ml and a sample standard deviation of 5.75 ml. Test the hypothesis that the mean amount of fluid is \(564\) ml at the \(5\%\) level.

Solution:

Our null and alternative hypotheses

  • \(H_0: \mu = 568\),

  • \(H_1: \mu \neq 568\).

We can now calculate our test statistic to be \[t =\displaystyle \frac{\overline{x} - \mu_0}{\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}} = \frac{566 - 564}{\frac{5.75}{\sqrt{30}}} = 1.91.\] The 0.975 quantile of a \(t_{29}\) distribution is 2.04 so since \(|1.91| < |2.04|\) we have insufficient evidence to reject \(H_0\) at this level.

10.4 Using confidence intervals to perform tests

Because test statistics and confidence intervals are constructed in very similar ways, we can use a 95% confidence interval to perform a test at the 5% level or and a 90% confidence interval to perform a test at the 10% level. The test is performed by checking whether the hypothesized value is contained within the interval or not. If it is in the interval then it is consistent with the null hypothesis and there isn’t sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis.

Example 10.3 The log of the current (in amps) in a circuit is modelled as a \(N(\mu, 1)\) distribution. A random sample of \(9\) currents at different times gives a mean of \(2.40\) amps. Calculate a 95 precent confidence interval for \(\mu\) and hence test, at the \(5\%\) level, the hypothesis that the mean current is \(3.50\) amps.

Solution:

Because \(\sigma\) is known, the 95% confidence interval is \[\begin{align} \overline{x} \pm z_{1-\frac{\alpha}{2}}\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}} &= 2.40 \pm 1.96 \times \frac{1}{\sqrt{9}}\\ &= 2.40 \pm 0.65\\ &= (1.75,3.05) \end{align}\] Our null and alternative hypotheses

  • \(H_0: \mu = 3.5\) amps,

  • \(H_1: \mu \neq 3.5\) amps.

Because 3.5 (\(\mu\)) is not in the 95 percent confidence interval we have sufficient evidence to reject \(H_0\) at the 5% level.

10.5 Goodness of fit tests

Consider the number of lorries arriving at a warehouse in hourly intervals. Is it plausible that the number of arrivals follows a Poisson distribution?

no. of arrivals per hour 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7
no. of hours 53 152 130 102 44 11 5 3

The general principle is to compare our observed table of counts, with what we would expect, if the null hypothesis is true. Define \(o_j\) and \(e_j\) to be the observed and expected count in cell \(j\) of the table respectively. The test statistic is \[\sum_{\text{all cells}}\frac{(o_j-e_j)^2}{e_j}.\]

Its null sampling distribution is a chi squared distributions, written \(\chi^2\). This is another family of distributions, indexed by a degrees of freedom parameter \(\nu\). It is not symmetric unlike the \(t\) or normal distribution (See Figure 10.2. To perform the test you need to calculate the expected counts in each cell, specify \(\nu\) and calculate the relevant quantiles from the \(\chi^2\) distribution.

Figure 10.2: A chi-squared distribution with 4 degrees of freedom.

We use the multinomial distribution (Section 5.3) to say how many observations of a particular type we would expect. We demonstrate this in Example 10.4.

Example 10.4 The numbers of lorries arriving at a warehouse in a given hour is expected to follow a Poisson distribution. The probability that \(k\) trucks arrive in an hour is \(\frac{\lambda^ke^{-\lambda}}{k!}\) for some \(\lambda\). The number of lorries arriving was counted over 500 separate hours with the following results:

no. of arrivals per hour 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7
no. of hours 53 152 130 102 44 11 5 3

Test the hypothesis that the arrivals are distributed in a Poisson distribution.

Solution:

The total number of lorries arriving in the 500 hours is 1000. Therefore the mean number per hour is 2 and so we infer that \(\lambda=2\).

[Check: \(0 \times 53 + 1 \times 152 + ...+7 \times 3 =1000]\)

Using the Po\((2)\), we can calculate the expected number of hours where there should be no arrivals. \(P(0)=\frac{2^0e^{-2}}{0!}=e^{-2}=0.135\), and since there are 500 hours sampled, we expect 67.7 hours where there should be no arrivals.

Similarly, the number of hours with \(1\) arrival is \(\frac{2^1e^{-2}}{1!}=2e^{-2}=0.271\) hence we expect \(135.3\) hours with one arrival etc. Hence

\(j\) 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7
\(o_j\) 53 152 130 102 44 11 5 3
\(e_j\) 67.7 135.3 135.3 90.2 45.1 18.0 6.0 2.3

The \(e_j\) do not need to be integers though the observed counts obviously are.

In this example there are never more than 7 lorries arriving in any hour but there could be. To allow for all possibilities we should really change the final cell to \(\geq 7\). We then calculate \(e_j\) by first finding \(P(X\geq 7)\). We do need to make the assumption \(X=7\) exactly in order to infer \(\lambda=2\).

The value of the test statistic is \(\sum^{7}_{j=0}\frac{\left(o_j-e_j\right)^2}{e_j}=10.13\).

The degrees of freedom are given by \(\nu=n-r-1\) where \(n\) is the number of cells and \(r\) is the number of parameters we have inferred (here just \(\lambda\)). This gives \(\nu=8-1-1=6\).

At the 5% level of test, the 0.95 quantile can be calculated using chi2inv\((0.95,6)=12.59\) in Matlab. Since \(10.13<12.59\) we have insufficient evidence at the 5 percent level to reject the null hypothesis that a Poisson probability model is a suitable model for the number of arrivals per hour at the warehouse. In other words, the \(Poisson(2)\) distribution is a plausible model for these data. Note that when finding quantiles using the \(\chi^2\) distribution we don`t split the probability between the two tails as we do for the normal and \(t\) distributions.
